Abdomen. Abdomen without gills, slightly flattened dorsoventrally (depressed), with purplish hue dorsally and whitish coloration laterally and ventrally. Abdominal segments I–VIII each with one pair of ventral (
Fig. 11 v
), two pairs of dorsal ( Fig. 11 ad, pd) and one pair of pleural setae ( Fig. 11 pl); in addition, abdominal segments II– VIII each with lateral longitudinal band of 25–35 short setae, creating ‘lateral fringe’ ( Fig. 11 , dotted oval). Last abdominal sternum (sternum IX) with 27–39 sternal setae; secondary setae usually much shorter than all 8 primary setae ( Fig. 12 op, ip, p). Abdominal dorsum IX without sclerite but with trio of setae on each side of body: one long primary seta ( Fig. 13 p ) and two tiny secondary posterolateral setae ( Fig. 13 is, os); outermost secondary seta ( Fig. 13 os) distinctly longer than median secondary seta ( Fig. 13 is).
